4. μοιχαλίδες.] Recent editors follow A. B. Sin. in omitting μοιχοὶ καί, and understand the word in the figurative sense of adulterous souls, in accordance with the language of the 0111, which speaks of Israel as married to Jeho‘v'ah (Isa. lvii. 3—9, Jer. iii. 20, Ezek. 16 esp. VV. 32, 35, 38, ib. ch. 23,Hosea ch. 2), and of the NT. which speaks of the Ohurch as the Lanib's Wife (2 Cor. xi. 1 2, Eph. v. 22—32, Apoc. xix. 7, ib. xxi. 9). It is less usual to find this figure used to express the relation of the individual soul to God, but cf. Psa. lxxiii. 27, Rom. vii. 2-4, Clem. 110111. 111. 28 ὁπόταν ἡ ψυχὴ ὑφ’ ἑτέρων σπαρῇ, τότε, ὡς πορνεύσασα ἢ μοιχευσαμένη, ὑπὸ τοῦ Πνεῦματος ἐγκαταλείπεται. The insertion of μοιχοί was natural when μοιχαλίς was understood literally, but the context and especially ver. 5 are in favour of the figurative meaning. [Spitta however takes it of litera] adultery, though he thinks the feminine is used tropically of both sexes when seduced by evil spirits] The word, which is unclassical (Lol).
